article.headline: Los Angeles takes season series heading into postseason
article.linkText: Mabika's 19 points help Sparks halt Comets
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Even in a game with no playoff implications,
there was still something at stake for the Los Angeles Sparks and
the Houston Comets.

The two-time defending champion Sparks beat the Comets 67-64
Monday night to close out the regular season on a five-game winning
streak.

"The game meant a lot to us because there is a huge rivalry
between the two teams," said DeLisha Milton, who had 15 points for
the Sparks. "There is pride and bragging rights at stake."

Mwadi Mabika scored 19 points, including six in the final two
minutes for Los Angeles.

"Anytime we play Houston it means something," said Tamecka
Dixon, who also had 19 points for the Sparks. "We wanted to send a
message and let them know that we are not to be played with going
into the playoffs. They are going in on a low note and we are going
in on a high note."

Sheryl Swoopes missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer for the Comets,
who lost three straight and four in a row on the road heading into
the playoffs.

"It was not like we had anything to lose or that they had
anything to lose, except for trying to get some momentum going into
the playoffs," Swoopes said.

Tina Thompson scored 19 points for the Comets and Swoopes added
13. Lisa Leslie added eight points and 14 rebounds for the Sparks.

"We played hard, but could not convert at the end of the
stretch," Thompson said. "They are very talented and they have so
many weapons to use on the court."

Dixon hit two free throws after a flagrant foul by Tiffani
Johnson, tying the game at 59 with 2:12 remaining.

Mabika made a 3-pointer, Thompson hit a turnaround jumper and
Michelle Snow scored on a fastbreak layup to put Houston back in
front 63-62.

Milton hit two free throws and Mabika made a pair for a 66-63
lead. Swoopes' bad pass led to a turnover with 27 seconds left.
Snow made one of two free throws to put Houston within two.

Mabika made one of two free throws for a 67-64 lead before
Swoopes missed the chance to force overtime.

"What a game," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "We can see
how the playoffs will be. It was a struggle, but I like how we kept
our composure down the stretch. We did all the little things that
it took to win this game."

The game between the only teams ever to win the WNBA
championship had no impact on the playoffs, which begin Thursday.
Los Angeles had already clinched its fourth consecutive Western
Conference title and the top-seeded Sparks will play No. 4
Minnesota in the first round.

"We've been through as much as we could possibly be through,
and we're still sitting atop the West and have a great chance to
three-peat," Dixon said. "It's been a long, hard-fought battle."

The No. 2 Comets open against third-seeded Sacramento.

"We showed it's going to be tough to play against us," Comets
guard Janeth Arcain said.

The Sparks won the season series 3-1, and swept both games in
Houston.

Houston led by two points at halftime and then built a 42-32
lead, helped by five consecutive points from Snow and a 3-pointer
by Thompson.

The Sparks answered with a 14-2 run, including Mabika's seven
points and Nikki Teasley's 3-pointer, for a 46-44 lead -- their
first of the second half -- with 10:35 remaining.

Neither team led by more than four points over the final 10
minutes.
